       "Euvolaemic hyponatraemia with concentrated urine, high urine sodium and normal thyroid/adrenal function is SIADH, here secondary to pneumonia. With mild symptoms and a likely chronic component, first-line treatment is fluid restriction, with correction limited to no more than 8 mmol/L in 24 hours - overly rapid correction of chronic hyponatraemia causes osmotic demyelination syndrome. Hypertonic saline is reserved for severe symptoms (seizures, coma) and even then is given in small boluses targeting a rise of only 4-6 mmol/L. Isotonic saline can paradoxically worsen SIADH because the kidney excretes the sodium and retains the water, and desmopressin would aggravate water retention.",
       "Euvolaemic hyponatraemia with concentrated urine = SIADH: fluid restrict and never correct chronic hyponatraemia faster than 8 mmol/L per day.",
