       "B",
       "Acute gout flares are treated with an NSAID, low-dose colchicine or corticosteroids, and established urate-lowering therapy should be continued unchanged through the flare. Stopping allopurinol causes urate flux that can prolong or precipitate further attacks, and the older practice of ceasing it during flares is no longer recommended. Increasing the dose acutely similarly destabilises urate levels without treating the inflammation. Septic arthritis is a key differential, but an afebrile systemically well man with a classic podagra picture and known gout does not require aspiration and antibiotics as first-line.",
       "Never stop (or start) allopurinol during an acute gout flare - treat the flare and leave urate-lowering therapy unchanged.",
