       "A minimal-trauma fracture in a woman over 50, especially with a densitometric T-score of -2.5 or below, is an unequivocal indication for antiresorptive therapy, and oral bisphosphonates (alendronate or risedronate) are first-line; denosumab and zoledronic acid are alternatives where oral therapy is unsuitable. Both the fracture and the T-score independently qualify her for PBS-subsidised treatment, so reassurance or a 2-year DXA delay leaves her exposed to high re-fracture risk - the first fracture is the strongest predictor of the next. MHT is not first-line for osteoporosis at 74, and teriparatide is reserved for severe disease after bisphosphonate failure.",
       "A minimal-trauma fracture over 50 means osteoporosis treatment is indicated - do not wait for further fractures or repeat scans.",
